[2] USA: doctor's false negative Ebola test
Date: 16 Nov 2014
Source: Washington Post [edited]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/a-doctors-mistaken-ebola-test-we-were-celebrating--then-everything-fell-apart/2014/11/16/946a84da-6dd5-11e4-a2c2-478179fd0489_story.html?wpisrc=nl-eve&wpmm=1


When [the doctor's] Ebola test came back negative, his friends and colleagues threw their arms around him. They shook his hand. They patted him on the back. They removed their protective gear and cried. But when his symptoms remained nearly a week later, [he] took another test, on 10 Nov 2014. This one came back positive, sending the Sierra Leonean doctor with ties to Maryland on a desperate, belated quest for treatment and forcing the colleagues who had embraced him into quarantine...

Although the United Methodist hospital where [the doctor] worked doesn't treat Ebola, doctors [there] knew that their patients could be infectious. A woman giving birth, a man complaining of abdominal pain, any of them could be carrying the disease. [The doctor] wore gloves but never the full protective gear used in the country's Ebola wards...

The doctors who tended to him in Freetown appeared to be unaware that an early Ebola test -- taken within the 1st 3 days of the illness -- is often inconclusive. In a country where information about the disease continues to move slowly, it was another potentially tragic mistake. In many cases, a negative test at that stage means nothing because "there aren't enough copies of the virus in the blood for the test to pick up," said Ermias Belay, the head of the CDC's Ebola response team in Sierra Leone...

And now, several other [health workers] who interacted closely with [the doctor] are quarantined [for 21 days]. So far, none are symptomatic. But all are frustrated that their celebration of what appeared to be good news ended this way... - more

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The lab that performed the 1st test should not be faulted, for the reason given, but the delay before the 2nd test meant that appropriate treatment was not started early enough to save him, and unlike other medevaced patients, he was too weak to walk from the ambulance to the hospital on arrival in the USA. - Mod.JW]

