[6] USA: passengers from Mali screened
Date: 16 Nov 2014
Source: Yahoo (AP) [edited]
https://news.yahoo.com/us-screen-travelers-mali-ebola-220329290.html


Travelers from Mali will be subject to the same screening and monitoring that was ordered for people arriving from 3 other Ebola-affected countries, U.S. health officials said Sunday [16 Nov 2014].

Mali is not suffering widespread Ebola illnesses, but federal officials are growing increasingly worried about a new cluster of 7 illnesses in Mali that have left public health workers scrambling to track and monitor [more than 440] other people who may have had contact with the 7 people and may be at risk.

"At this point, we can't be confident that every exposed person has been identified, or that every identified person is being monitored daily," said Dr. Tom Frieden, director of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC].

Starting Mon [17 Nov 2014], anyone arriving in the USA from Mali will undergo the same screening procedures that were ordered last month [October 2014] for travelers from Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea. That includes taking arriving travelers' temperatures and questioning them about their health and possible exposure to the Ebola virus. They also will be asked to provide contact information and to agree to have daily communications with local health officials -- for 21 days -- who will be asking them to take their temperatures twice each day and monitoring them to see whether they develop symptoms.

West Africa is currently suffering the worst Ebola epidemic in world history, with at least 14 000 illnesses and more than 5100 deaths so far. Nearly all of the cases have been in Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone. About 75 people arrive from those 3 countries each day, on average. They are funneled through 5 airports, 2 in New York and one each in Washington, Chicago and Atlanta. In contrast, only about 15 to 20 passengers arrive from Mali to the United States on an average day. The majority end up arriving through the same 5 airports. But in the next few days, steps will be taken to make sure all funnel through those airports, Frieden said... - more

